Acer grandidentatum is a species of maple tree native to North America. 
It typically grows to be 15-50 feet tall, with a rounded or oval-shaped crown. 
The bark is grayish-brown and develops vertical grooves over time. 
The leaves are large and toothed, typically measuring between 3 and 6 inches in length. 
In the fall, they turn shades of yellow, orange, and red. 
The tree produces greenish-yellow flowers in the spring, which develop into winged fruits known as samaras. 
Acer grandidentatum is commonly found in mountainous regions and is used for ornamental and landscaping purposes.
